Part 1: Data

1) What is the description of this data?

These data are about health surveys that collect state data about U.S. residents regarding their health-related risk behaviors, chronic health conditions, and use of preventive services. Conducted by Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System (BRFSS), a collaborative project between all of the states in the United States (US) and participating US territories and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC).

2) Why is this data collected?

BRFSS has become a powerful tool for targeting and building health promotion activities. The BRFSS objective is to collect uniform, state-specific data on preventive health practices and risk behaviors that are linked to chronic diseases, injuries, and preventable infectious diseases that affect the adult population.

3) How the observations in the sample are collected?

A cross-sectional telephone survey that state health departments conduct monthly over landline telephones and cellular telephones with a standardized questionnaire and technical and methodologic assistance from CDC. In order to conduct the BRFSS, states obtain samples of telephone numbers from CDC. States then review their sampling methodology with a state statistician and CDC to make sure data collection procedures are in place to follow the methodology. If any change in sampling methodology is considered, states consult with CDC before making changes.

The BRFSS uses two samples: one for landline telephone respondents and one for cellular telephone respondents. - The Landline Sample: Disproportionate stratified sampling (DSS) has been used for the landline sample since 2003. The DSS design attempts to find a way of differentiating, before sampling begins, between a set of telephone numbers that contains a large proportion of target numbers (the high-density block) and a set that contains a smaller proportion of target numbers (the medium-density block. DSS sampling telephone numbers is more efficient than simple random sampling. - The Cellular Telephone Sample: The cellular telephone sample is randomly generated from a sampling frame of confirmed cellular area code and prefix combinations.

1- Reasoning for generalizability:

As presented in the course, random sampling happens when subjects are selected randomly from the population. We can affirm that BRFSS uses random sampling, as each subject in the population is equally likely to be selected, and the resulting sample is likely representative of the population. So the study’s results are generalizable to the population at large, in this case about U.S. residents. The only point is that BRFSS use randomly generated for cellular telephone respondent’s sample, and disproportionate stratified sampling (a stratified sampling procedure) for landline. P.S. States complete approximately 20% of their completed interviews with respondents on cell phones.

2- Reasoning for causality: On the other hand, the BRFSS does not use random assignment, since it only occurs in experimental settings, where subjects are being assigned to various treatments. Therefore, it is not possible to make causal conclusions based on the study, since we can’t ensure that some different characteristics between subjects are represented equally in the treatment and control groups and consequently don’t allow us to attribute any observed difference between the treatment and control groups.

Part 2: Research questions

Research question 1: What is the total of answers by sex and general Health, and the highest responses by state?

In my first question, I want to see the big picture of the data and have a view of the proportion of general health by sex and the top ten responses by state.

Research question 2: What is the relativity of the US citizens who have any health care coverage or could not see dr. because of cost and general Health? Additionally what is the education level, employment status and income level for those who had health care coverage?

The second question is related to the social and economic condition with the medical coverage and how it reflects on general Health.

Research question 3: What is the relativity of the US citizens who smoked at least 100 cigarettes in entire life, or been told by a health professional that your blood cholesterol is high and did exercise in the past 30 days?

Third research question involves seeing the relativity of the US citizens who smoked cigarettes in their entire life or had high cholesterol with the practice of exercise. * * *

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

Research question 1

unique(brfss2013$iyear)
## [1] 2013 2014 <NA>
## Levels: 2013 2014
### Make sure that we are only going to look at 2013 data:
group2013 <- brfss2013 %>%
filter(iyear == "2013")

groupstate <- group2013%>%
  group_by(X_state) %>%
  summarise(total = n())

names(groupstate)[names(groupstate) == "n"] <- "total"

## Rename columns
group2013 <- group2013 %>% rename(month = imonth,
                                  health_care = hlthpln1,
                                  general_health = genhlth,
                                  not_dr_cost = medcost,
                                  press_medication = bpmeds,
                                  heart_attack = cvdinfr4,
                                  overweight_obese = X_rfbmi5,
                                  cholest_high = toldhi2,
                                  satisf_life = lsatisfy
                                  )

groupstate %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = total)) +
  geom_histogram()

Evaluation In this histogram by state we can see that it is a positive skew distribution. This usually happens when it has a few relatively high values and the mean is greater than the median.

groupstate %>%

group2013 %>%
  group_by(month) %>%
  summarise(n = n()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = month, y = n, group = 1)) + 
    geom_line()

Evaluation January we have fewer respondents than the rest of the year and Florida has the largest number of respondents.

groupsex <- group2013%>%
  group_by(sex) %>%
  summarise(n = n()) %>%
  na.exclude

groupsex$prop <- groupsex$n / sum(groupsex$n)

groupsex %>% 
  mutate(prop = prop.table(n),
         prop = sprintf("%0.2f", prop)
         )
## # A tibble: 2 x 3
##   sex         n prop 
##   <fct>   <int> <chr>
## 1 Male   198974 0.41 
## 2 Female 287112 0.59
groupsexhlt <- group2013%>%
group_by(sex, general_health) %>%
summarise(n = n())
groupsexhlt <- na.omit(groupsexhlt)

groupsex %>% 
  mutate(prop=scales::percent(prop))  %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=sex,y=prop))+
  geom_bar(stat="identity",color='black',fill='orange')+
  xlab("Gender informed")+ylab("Gender Ratio of US citizens ") +
  geom_text(aes(label=prop), position=position_dodge(width=0.4), vjust=0, size = 5) + coord_flip()

groupsexhlt %>% 
     group_by(sex) %>%
     mutate(n_perc = prop.table(n)) %>%
     ggplot(aes(x=sex, y=n, label=scales::percent(n_perc), fill=general_health)) + 
     geom_bar(position="fill", stat="identity") +
     geom_text(size = 4, position = position_fill(vjust = 0.5)) +
     scale_y_continuous(label = scales::percent)

Evaluation Female citizens have greater representation in the respondents, but the general health is very similar to male.

Research question 2

group2013 %>%
  group_by(general_health, health_care) %>%
  summarise(n = n(), n_perc = prop.table(n)) %>%
  
  na.exclude %>%
  
  group_by(health_care) %>%
  mutate(n_perc = prop.table(n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=health_care, y=n, label=scales::percent(n_perc), fill=general_health)) +
    geom_bar(position="fill", stat="identity") +
    geom_text(size = 4, position = position_fill(vjust = 0.5)) +
    scale_y_continuous(label = scales::percent)

group2013 %>%
  group_by(not_dr_cost, general_health) %>%
  summarise(n = n(), n_perc = prop.table(n)) %>%
  
  na.exclude %>%
  
  group_by(not_dr_cost) %>%
  mutate(n_perc = prop.table(n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=not_dr_cost, y=n, label=scales::percent(n_perc), fill=general_health)) +
    geom_bar(position="fill", stat="identity") +
    geom_text(size = 4, position = position_fill(vjust = 0.5)) +
    scale_y_continuous(label = scales::percent)

Evaluation We can evaluate that the US citizens who answered ‘YES’ for Have Any Health Care Coverage have a greater representativeness in the responses of very good and excellent for general health, when compared with those who answered ‘NO’. And when we look to the question “Could Not See Dr. Because Of Cost?” we see that those who answered ‘YES’ have a greater representativeness in the responses of Poor and Fair general health.

This means that the fact of having any health care coverage and the cost of see a dr. impacts directly on the US citizens’ general health.

Research question 3

group2013%>%
  group_by(heart_attack,strength) %>%
  summarise(n = n()) %>% 
  na.exclude %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = strength, fill=heart_attack)) +
    geom_histogram(color="black") +
    xlab("how many times per week or per month did you do physical activities or exercises") +
    ylab("Had a heart attack") + 
    scale_fill_manual(values=c("hotpink1", "steelblue2"))

Evaluation From the graph, we can say that people who hadn’t been diagnosed with a heart attack practice more exercises per week than those who have been.

  group2013 %>%

Evaluation From the graph, we can say that people who had been told that their blood cholesterol is high practice fewer exercises per week than those who haven’t been informed.

In addition, in the last graph we can see that obese people or with over weight doesn’t change significant with those who aren’t, about the satisfaction with life.
